            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.I.R2</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Marseilles &ndash; Hot dusty picture&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-8a253f21-7fff-bbe9-39a5-60232ee893d7\"><br />The novel begins with this hot dusty picture of &ldquo;Marseilles&hellip;burning in the sun, one day&rdquo; (LD 1), with the &ldquo;staring habit&rdquo; created by the incessant still heat. Dust appears three times in the opening scene: the &ldquo;staring roads&rdquo; are &ldquo;deep in dust&rdquo; (1); the vines on the cottages are &ldquo;dusty&rdquo;; and &ldquo;[t]he very dust was scorched brown&rdquo; (2). This chapter echoes and elaborates on Dickens&rsquo;s earlier depiction of Marseilles in <em>Pictures from Italy</em>, in which he had described the &ldquo;dreadful&rdquo; heat of Marseilles, the &ldquo;country-houses&hellip;always staring white,&rdquo; and the &ldquo;dust, dust, dust, everywhere&rdquo; (<em>Pictures</em> 27). </span></p>"
